SIMPLE: indivisible
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indivisible
<hw>In`di*vis"i*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>indivisibilis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>indivisible</ets>. See
<er>In-</er> not, and <er>Divisible</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not divisible; incapable of being divided,
separated, or broken; not separable into parts.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧One
<xex>indivisible</xex> point of time.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Not capable of exact division, as
one quantity by another; incommensurable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indivisible</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Indivisible
<hw>In`di*vis"i*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
indivisible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By atom, nobody will imagine we intend to express a perfect
<qex>indivisible</qex>, but only the least sort of natural bodies.</q>
<rj><qau>Digby.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>An infinitely small quantity
which is assumed to admit of no further division.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Method of indivisibles</b></col>, <cd>a kind of calculus,
formerly in use, in which lines were considered as made up of an
infinite number of points; surfaces, as made up of an infinite number of
lines; and volumes, as made up of an infinite number of
surfaces.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indivisibleness</ent>⟦br⟧
